<paper id="1518813605"><title>Computing Answers for Disjunctive Logic Programs</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="University of Koblenz" id="2704057665">Ulrich Furbach</author></authors><n_citation>5</n_citation><doc_type /><references><reference>55851624</reference><reference>188042260</reference><reference>191908603</reference><reference>1514729613</reference><reference>1520081795</reference><reference>1529387115</reference><reference>1530765221</reference><reference>1591091340</reference><reference>1605976683</reference><reference>2082367267</reference><reference>2084894656</reference><reference>2148853609</reference><reference>2568236667</reference></references><venue id="" type="">JELIA '92 Proceedings of the European Workshop on Logics in AI</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0023438</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.65986">Model elimination</keyword><keyword weight="0.66544">Functional logic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.46094">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.70738">Horn clause</keyword><keyword weight="0.43939">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61522">Disjunctive normal form</keyword><keyword weight="0.45277">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.67867">Stable model semantics</keyword><keyword weight="0.69009">Logic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.68955">Predicate functor logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.66207">Dynamic logic (modal logic)</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Various approaches to computing answers for disjunctive logic programs are presented. Emphasis is put on splitting based approaches; a naive application of the splitting rule is taken as a starting point for both, the development of a fixpoint semantics and the Split-Sld-calculus. This calculus is proven correct and complete and it is compared with model elimination and InH-Prolog.</abstract></paper>